| {{convert|24|cm|in|abbr=on}}{{ref|Height|1}}
| Nisa Juarez
| [[Baby]]
| Was born 108 days premature and weighed only {{convert|320|g|abbr=on|sigfig=3}}.<ref>GWR 2006, p. 17.</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/shortest-baby | title = World's shortest baby | publisher = guinnessworldrecords.com | accessdate = 28 April 2017}}</ref>
| 2002 –
|-
| {{flagcountry|United States}}
| {{convert|53.3|cm|in|abbr=on}}{{ref|Height|2}}
| [[Francis Joseph Flynn]]
| Teenager<ref name=Ruoff>{{cite book |last=Ruoff |first=Henry W. |title=The Standard dictionary of facts : history, language, literature, biography... |year=1922 |publisher=Frontier Press |oclc=21954748 |page=786 |quote=twenty-one inches at sixteen}}</ref>
| General Mite, was an American dwarf who performed as a showman at various competitions around the world. In 1884, Flynn married English little person, Millie Edwards, in England.<ref>{{cite book |last=Haydn |first=Joseph |author2=Benjamin Vincent  |title=[[Haydn's Dictionary of Dates|Haydn's Dictionary of Dates and Universal Information Relating to All Ages ...]] |year=1906 |publisher=[[G. P. Putnam's Sons]] |oclc=12934491 |page= 419}}</ref> The wedding was widely publicized and attended. From then on, the couple were exhibited as the "Royal American Midgets" and "General and Mrs. Mite" in many advertisements.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |title=DETAILS OF THE MIDGETS' MARRIAGE. |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1884/06/15/103620650.pdf |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=15 June 1884 |format=PDF |accessdate=2008-06-18 |page=6}}</ref>
| 1864–1898
|- style="background:#d0f0c0;"
| {{flagcountry|United States}}
| {{convert|72.4|cm|in|abbr=on}}
| Stacey Herald
| Mother{{ref|Height|3}}
| Stacey gave birth to her first child on 21 October 2006, and later birthed two more children all of which were delivered by [[caesarean sections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/shortest-woman-to-give-birth|title=Shortest woman to give birth|publisher=Guinness World Records|accessdate=27 April 2017}}</ref>
| {{unknown}}
|- 
| {{flagcountry|Hungary}}
| {{convert|101.5|cm|in|abbr=on}}<ref name="GWR 1990">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y8Pm70o2tmoC&q=Susanna+Bokoyni+height&dq=Susanna+Bokoyni+height&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiIm_Lbza7eAhXGwFkKHXW_CkMQ6AEIKDAA|title=Guinness Book of World Records (1990)|author=Donald McFarlan & Norris McWhirter|publisher=Bantam|page=8|year=1990|accessdate=October 30, 2018}}</ref>
| [[Susanna Bokoyni]]
| [[Longevity]]
| Bokoyni died at the age of 105, making her the oldest verified centenarian dwarf. During her lifetime she travelled with various circuses where she was a performer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HC7Z4Gjnd88C&q=%22Susanna+Bokoyni%22&dq=%22Susanna+Bokoyni%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=V20hT67sN_P2sQKptJDDCQ&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA|title=The Guinness Book of World Records 1997|first=Norris|last=McWhirter|date=1 March 1997|publisher=Bantam Books.|via=Google Books}}</ref>
| 1879–1984
|}

