{{Infobox rockunit | name = Quseir Formation | period = Campanian | age = {{fossilrange|Campanian}} | image = | imagesize = | caption = | type = [[Geological formation]] | prilithology = [[Shale]] | otherlithology = [[Sandstone]], [[Siltstone]], [[Phosphorite]] | unitof = | subunits = Mut Member, El Hindaw Member | underlies = [[Duwi Formation]] | overlies = Unconformity with [[Taref Formation]] | thickness = at least {{Convert|250|m|ft}} | area = | map = | map_caption = <!----Location----> | location = | coordinates = | region = [[Kharga Oasis]] | country = {{flag|Egypt}} | extent = }}
The '''Quseir Formation''' is a [[Geological Formation]] in the vicinity of the [[Kharga Oasis]] in [[Egypt]]. It is [[Campanian]] In age. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mahmoud|first=Magdy S.|date=2003-04|title=Palynology and palaeoenvironment of the Quseir Formation (Campanian) from central Egypt|url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0899536203000472|journal=Journal of African Earth Sciences|volume=36|issue=3|pages=135–148|doi=10.1016/s0899-5362(03)00047-2|issn=1464-343X}}</ref> The lithology largely consists of soft shale with hard bands of sandstone, siltstone and phosphorite.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sallam|first=Hesham M.|last2=O'Connor|first2=Patrick M.|last3=Kora|first3=Mahmoud|last4=Sertich|first4=Joseph J.W.|last5=Seiffert|first5=Erik R.|last6=Faris|first6=Mahmoud|last7=Ouda|first7=Khaled|last8=El-Dawoudi|first8=Iman|last9=Saber|first9=Sara|date=2016-05|title=Vertebrate paleontological exploration of the Upper Cretaceous succession in the Dakhla and Kharga Oases, Western Desert, Egypt|url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1464343X16300334|journal=Journal of African Earth Sciences|volume=117|pages=223–234|doi=10.1016/j.jafrearsci.2016.01.022|issn=1464-343X}}</ref>The environment of deposition was nearshore to freshwater fluvio-lacustrine characterized by moist and aquatic habitats with a tropical warm-humid climate. It is comformably overlain by the marine late Campanian-[[Maastrichtian]] Duwi Formation, and unconformably overlies the [[Turonian]] Taref Formation. The dinosaur ''[[Mansourasaurus]]'' was discovered in the formation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sallam|first=Hesham M.|last2=Gorscak|first2=Eric|last3=O’Connor|first3=Patrick M.|last4=El-Dawoudi|first4=Iman A.|last5=El-Sayed|first5=Sanaa|last6=Saber|first6=Sara|last7=Kora|first7=Mahmoud A.|last8=Sertich|first8=Joseph J. W.|last9=Seiffert|first9=Erik R.|date=2018-01-29|title=New Egyptian sauropod reveals Late Cretaceous dinosaur dispersal between Europe and Africa|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/s41559-017-0455-5|journal=Nature Ecology & Evolution|language=En|volume=2|issue=3|pages=445–451|doi=10.1038/s41559-017-0455-5|issn=2397-334X}}</ref>, Additionally the lungfish genera ''[[Lavocatodus]] and [[Protopterus]]'' <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Claeson|first=Kerin M|last2=Sallam|first2=Hesham M|last3=O'Connor|first3=Patrick M.|last4=Sertich|first4=Joseph J. W.|date=2014|title=A revision of the Upper Cretaceous lepidosirenid lungfishes from the Quseir Formation, Western Desert, central Egypt|url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/02724634.2014.838574?journalCode=ujvp20|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume=34|issue=4|pages=760-766|via=}}</ref> and the Crocodyliform ''[[Wahasuchus]]''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Saber|first=Sara|last2=Sertich|first2=Joseph J.W.|last3=Sallam|first3=Hesham M.|last4=Ouda|first4=Khaled A.|last5=O'Connor|first5=Patrick M.|last6=Seiffert|first6=Erik R.|date=2018-10|title=An enigmatic crocodyliform from the Upper Cretaceous Quseir Formation, central Egypt|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0195667117301453|journal=Cretaceous Research|volume=90|pages=174–184|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2018.04.004|issn=0195-6671}}</ref> are also known.
